        (6002,'main','heatmap','scale','0.5','Heatmap scale','text',0,'blank,numeric','size=5','The scale represents the size of the heatmap to generate. \r\n\r\nA scale of 1 means the heatmap will be the same resolution as the map overlay and has no loss of detail. A scale of 0.5 means the heatmap would be 1/2 the size, and a scale of 2 would be double the size. When a heatmap is displayed on top of a map overlay image it is stretched automatically to fit the actual overlay image.\r\n\r\nThe larger the heatmap the longer it takes to process the image and the larger the file or database storage is required.\r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> 0.5 (with a brush size of \'medium\')'),
        (6003,'main','heatmap','brush','medium','Heatmap brush size','select',0,'blank','small:Small (9x9)\r\nmedium:Medium (25x25)\r\nlarge:Large (53x53)','The brush size determines how large the heatmap plots are. A small brush will produce very small \'dots\' on the heatmap and shows a very detailed heatmap. A large brush size causes more \'heat\' to be applied and causes larger areas to be consumed on the overlay. \r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> Medium (with a scale of 0.5)'),
        (6006,'main','heatmap','maxdays','365','Max days spatial data','text',0,'blank,numeric','size=5','Maximum days of spatial data to keep for heatmaps. A months worth of spatial data on an active server can be roughly 10-15MB and over 300k samples of data.\r\n\r\nAnything past about a month or so will not generally provide any more detail on heatmaps.\r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> 1-2 months'),
        (6007,'main','heatmap','dir','','Directory','text',0,'','','By default, heatmaps are stored in the database so they can be retrieved from the webserver w/o any file permission or location problems. If your psychostats installation is run from another machine you must store heatmaps in the database.\r\n\r\nHeatmaps will be saved in the directory specified, or if left blank they will be saved in the database.\r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> If stats.pl is run on this web server then specify a directory that is accessible to the web server. Otherwise leave this blank.'),
        (6008,'main','heatmap','expires','3600','Expire Cache','text',0,'numeric','size=5','How many seconds a heatmap image can be cached on the client\'s browser. This is a per-client setting and does not always force a heatmap image to be cached. Typically, a user\'s browser will cache the images it downloads for a short period and will not re-download the image unless the user forces the browser to reload all images. If left blank, no expires header is sent to the client.\r\n\r\nThis setting will help reduce load on your web server. <b>Only works on Apache web servers!</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> 1 hour (3600 seconds)'),
        (6009,'theme',NULL,'overlays_dir','','Images: Overlays directory','text',0,'','','Absolute root directory where map overlay images are located. These images are used for heatmaps.\r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> Leave blank for default. (auto-discovered)'),
        (6010,'theme',NULL,'overlays_url','','Images: Overlays URL','text',0,'','','Absolute URL for map overlay images. This should match up to the location of the \"Overlays directory\" setting. So the images can be referenced within the theme output correctly.\r\n\r\n<b>Recommendation:</b> Leave blank for default (auto-discovered)'),
